   <conbody>
      <div class="- topic/div ">
         <hazardstatement type="warning" class="+ topic/note hazard-d/hazardstatement ">
            <messagepanel class="+ topic/ul hazard-d/messagepanel ">
               <typeofhazard class="+ topic/li hazard-d/typeofhazard ">ENERGIZED BY external power sources</typeofhazard>
               <howtoavoid class="+ topic/li hazard-d/howtoavoid ">When emergency power off (EPO) is activated the load is
no longer supplied by the system. The system is still energized by
external input power sources and/or by the batteries.</howtoavoid>
            </messagepanel>
         </hazardstatement>
         <p platform="PxW WxW" class="- topic/p ">According
to UPS safety standard IEC 62040-1 (2017), a UPS with an emergency
switch device should be able to prevent further supply of the load.
The emergency switching device can interrupt the load internally,
or via a terminal to an externally connected switching device.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">The emergency power off (EPO) is integrated on the external connection
board <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">A025</b>. To use the EPO J3 needs to be open on <b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">A025</b>.</p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">There are two types of the EPO:<ul class="- topic/ul ">
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">EPO with internal power supply (J2 closed). Activates when
X107:1 and X107:2 is open.</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">EPO with external power supply (J2 open), voltage range: 9-24
V DC. Activates when X107:1 and X107:2 is open or when the external
power supply to X107:3 and X107:4 is off.</p>
                  <note class="- topic/note ">The EPO is fail-safe
in both options.</note>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </p>
         <p platform="PxW" class="- topic/p ">With EPO the load is de-energized by turning
off the system (Standby), the rectifier, the inverter and the static
switch(es).</p>
         <p platform="WxW" class="- topic/p ">With EPO the load is de-energized
by turning off the system (Standby), the inverter and the static switch(es).</p>
         <p platform="SDC" class="- topic/p ">With EPO the rectifier is turned off and the system
is in standby.</p>
